For this, you can make a list of lists.

    std::list&lt;std::list&lt;int&gt;&gt; my_list;

Accessing this list works just like you how access the integers.

    for(auto l: my_list){
        list&lt;int&gt;::iterator current_iterator = l.begin();
        //Do the rest of your work here
    }

You have an unknown (at compile time) number of elements of the same typ (`std::list` in your example). Your go to solution should be `std::vector`, so `std::vector&lt;std::list&lt;int&gt;&gt;` in your example:

```
int main()
{
    int n = 3; // get at runtime

    std::vector&lt;std::list&lt;int&gt;&gt; lists(n); // n lists

    // for each list
    for(auto&amp; list : lists)
    {
        // populate the list
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; 3; ++i)
        {
            list.push_back(i);
        }
    }

    // for each list
    for (auto&amp; list : lists)
    {
        // remove the element you want

        auto it = list.begin();
        std::advance(it, 1);

        list.erase(it);
    }
}
```

A `std::list` can hold almost any type (there are of course some requirements, see [here](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/container/list) for details). It can also hold `std::list&lt;int&gt;`s as elements, that would be 


    std::list&lt; std::list&lt;int&gt; &gt; list_of_lists;

Note that your example is a good case for `std::list` (erasing an element in the middle), however in general `std::vector` out-performs `std::list` for most applications due to memory locality. When in doubt make `std::vector` the default and compare.

