It looks like you are needing to rename your files using `TitleCase`. Note, converting to `TitleCase` does not work for all upper. So, we will need to put the string `ToLower()`:

    Get-ChildItem -Path &quot;C:\Path&quot; -Recurse | Rename-Item -NewName {$_.Name -replace &quot;$($_.Name)&quot;, &quot;$((Get-Culture).TextInfo.ToTitleCase($_.Name.ToLower()))&quot;}

Another note, this will change &quot;RX PPLLC&quot; to `TitleCase` as well. If you need to ignore that, you might need to use `substring` to get around it. 

Update: -- If you want to keep &quot;RX PPLLC&quot;:

    Get-ChildItem -Path &quot;C:\Test&quot; -Recurse | Rename-Item -NewName {
        $lefSide = $_.Name.Substring(0,$_.Name.IndexOf(&#39;-&#39;))
        $rightSide = $_.Name.Substring($_.Name.IndexOf(&#39;-&#39;) + 1)
        $rightSide = $((Get-Culture).TextInfo.ToTitleCase($rightSide.ToLower()))
        $newName = $leftSide + $rightSide
        $_.Name -replace &quot;$($_.Name)&quot;, &quot;$newName&quot;    
    }
There are much better ways of doing this. Basically, this will take the file name into two strings (a left side and right side). It will change the right then put it back into a variable called `$newName` . This will only work if your file name contains a `-`. If you wanted to handle for those situations, you would need a condition or a regEx... this is just a quick example

After hours of searching, it turns out that my encoding issue is caused by resources filtering set to true in the project&#39;s POM:

    	&lt;resources&gt;
